Consider the following grammar along with translation rules:

S -> S # T   { S.val = S1.val * T.val }
S -> T        { S.val = T.val }
T -> T / R   { T.val = T1.val / R.val }
T -> R        { T.val = R.val }
R -> R ! id  { R.val = R1.val ^ id.val }
R -> id       { R.val = id.val }

Here # and ! are operators and id is a token that represents an integer and id.val represents the corresponding integer value. The set of terminals is {#, !, /} and a subscripted non-terminal indicates an instance of the non-terminal.

Using this translation scheme, the computed value of S.val for the root of the parse tree for the expression 20#10/5#7/2!2 is ___.

Consider the following syntax-directed translation given by the following grammar and semantic rules. Here N, I, F, and B are non-terminals. N is the start non-terminal, and B and I denote occurrences of 0 and 1 on the right hand side of a production, respectively. X.val denotes the synthesized (numeric) value associated with a non-terminal X.

N -> I.F   { N.val = I.val + F.val }
N -> I     { N.val = I.val }
I -> I,B   { I.val = 2*I1.val + B.val }
I -> B     { I.val = B.val }
F -> B,F1  { F.val = (B.val + F1.val) / 2 }
F -> B     { F.val = B.val / 2 }
B -> 0     { B.val = 0 }
B -> 1     { B.val = 1 }

The value computed by the translation scheme for the input string 10#001 is ________. (Rounded off to three decimal places)
